576.answer:
A trie is a tree-based data structure for storing strings by their prefixes. Each edge represents a character, and each node represents a prefix built from the path from the root.

### What problems it solves
- **Fast prefix lookups**: Efficiently answers questions like “does any word start with `app`?”
- **Dictionary membership**: Checks whether a full word exists.
- **Autocomplete/search suggestions**: Natural fit for prefix-based completion.
- **Shared-prefix storage**: Words with common beginnings reuse nodes, which can be memory-efficient in some datasets.

### Why use it instead of a hash set?
A hash set is great for exact word lookup, but it does **not** efficiently support prefix queries. A trie supports both exact lookup and prefix lookup in **O(m)** time, where `m` is the length of the input string.

### Time complexity
For a word/prefix of length `m`:
- `insert(word)`: **O(m)**
- `search(word)`: **O(m)**
- `startsWith(prefix)`: **O(m)**

---

## JavaScript implementation

```js
class TrieNode {
  constructor() {
    this.children = new Map();
    this.isEndOfWord = false;
  }
}

class Trie {
  constructor() {
    this.root = new TrieNode();
  }

  insert(word) {
    let node = this.root;

    for (const char of word) {
      if (!node.children.has(char)) {
        node.children.set(char, new TrieNode());
      }
      node = node.children.get(char);
    }

    node.isEndOfWord = true;
  }

  search(word) {
    let node = this.root;

    for (const char of word) {
      if (!node.children.has(char)) {
        return false;
      }
      node = node.children.get(char);
    }

    return node.isEndOfWord;
  }

  startsWith(prefix) {
    let node = this.root;

    for (const char of prefix) {
      if (!node.children.has(char)) {
        return false;
      }
      node = node.children.get(char);
    }

    return true;
  }
}
```

### Example

```js
const trie = new Trie();

trie.insert("apple");
console.log(trie.search("apple"));    // true
console.log(trie.search("app"));      // false
console.log(trie.startsWith("app"));  // true

trie.insert("app");
console.log(trie.search("app"));      // true
```

