JSON serialization turns in-memory data into a JSON string; parsing does the reverse by turning a JSON string back into data. Serialization is useful for storage, APIs, and logging, while parsing is used when reading JSON from files, requests, or other systems. Safe handling means catching parse errors instead of assuming the input is valid.

```js
function prettyPrintJson(jsonString) {
  try {
    const value = JSON.parse(jsonString);
    return { ok: true, value: JSON.stringify(value, null, 2) };
  } catch (error) {
    return {
      ok: false,
      error: error instanceof Error ? error.message : 'Invalid JSON',
    };
  }
}

// Example usage
console.log(prettyPrintJson('{"name":"Seif","items":[1,2,3]}'));
console.log(prettyPrintJson('{name:}'));
```

