593.answer:
Idempotency means repeating the same request has the same intended effect on server state as doing it once. In REST, `PUT` is defined as idempotent because sending the same full representation to the same resource repeatedly should keep that resource in the same final state.

Typical implications:
- `PUT /users/123` with the same body 1 time or 10 times should leave `/users/123` identical.
- The response may differ across calls (for example, first returns `200`, later `200` again, or metadata like timestamps/logs may change), but the resource state should not keep changing.
- `POST` is usually not idempotent because repeating it often creates multiple resources.

Example Node.js handler using Express.

```js
app.put('/users/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const { id } = req.params;
  const replacement = req.body;

  if (!replacement || typeof replacement !== 'object' || Array.isArray(replacement)) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid user body' });
  }

  if (replacement.id !== undefined && String(replacement.id) !== id) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Body id must match path id' });
  }

  const user = {
    id,
    name: replacement.name,
    email: replacement.email,
  };

  const exists = await db.users.findById(id);

  if (!exists) {
    await db.users.insert(user);
    return res.status(201).json(user);
  }

  await db.users.replace(id, user);
  return res.status(200).json(user);
});
```

