752.answer:
Merge sort is a **divide-and-conquer** algorithm:

- Split the array into two halves.
- Recursively sort each half.
- Merge the two sorted halves into one sorted array.

Why it works:
- A 0- or 1-element array is already sorted.
- If both halves are sorted, you can combine them by repeatedly taking the smaller front element.

Properties:
- Time: **O(n log n)** in all cases
- Space: **O(n)** extra space for the merged arrays
- It is stable if implemented to preserve equal-element order

JavaScript implementation:

```js
function mergeSort(arr) {
  if (arr.length <= 1) {
    return arr;
  }

  const mid = Math.floor(arr.length / 2);
  const left = mergeSort(arr.slice(0, mid));
  const right = mergeSort(arr.slice(mid));

  return merge(left, right);
}

function merge(left, right) {
  const result = [];
  let i = 0;
  let j = 0;

  while (i < left.length && j < right.length) {
    if (left[i] <= right[j]) {
      result.push(left[i]);
      i++;
    } else {
      result.push(right[j]);
      j++;
    }
  }

  while (i < left.length) {
    result.push(left[i]);
    i++;
  }

  while (j < right.length) {
    result.push(right[j]);
    j++;
  }

  return result;
}
```

Example:

```js
console.log(mergeSort([5, 2, 9, 1, 3]));
// [1, 2, 3, 5, 9]
```

