769.answer:
A greedy algorithm builds a solution step by step by always taking the locally best choice at each step. It works well when the problem has the **greedy-choice property** (a locally optimal choice can lead to a globally optimal solution) and **optimal substructure** (after making a choice, the remaining problem is still an optimal subproblem).

For the **activity selection problem**, the greedy rule is:

- Sort activities by increasing **finish time**
- Always pick the next activity whose start time is at least the finish time of the last chosen one

Why this works:
- Choosing the activity that finishes earliest leaves the most room for future activities
- Any optimal solution can be transformed to start with that earliest-finishing compatible activity without reducing the number selected

## C++ solution

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

using namespace std;

struct Activity {
    int start;
    int finish;
};

int main() {
    int n;
    cin >> n;

    vector<Activity> activities(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        cin >> activities[i].start >> activities[i].finish;
    }

    sort(activities.begin(), activities.end(), [](const Activity& a, const Activity& b) {
        if (a.finish == b.finish) return a.start < b.start;
        return a.finish < b.finish;
    });

    vector<Activity> selected;
    int lastFinish = -1;

    for (const auto& activity : activities) {
        if (activity.start >= lastFinish) {
            selected.push_back(activity);
            lastFinish = activity.finish;
        }
    }

    cout << selected.size() << "\n";
    for (const auto& activity : selected) {
        cout << activity.start << " " << activity.finish << "\n";
    }

    return 0;
}
```

## Example

Input:
```text
6
1 4
3 5
0 6
5 7
8 9
5 9
```

Possible output:
```text
3
1 4
5 7
8 9
```

## Complexity
- Sorting: `O(n log n)`
- Selection scan: `O(n)`
- Total: `O(n log n)`

