A hash table stores key/value pairs and uses a **hash function** to convert a key into an array index called a **bucket**.

### Core idea
- Compute `index = hash(key) % bucketCount`
- Store the entry in that bucket
- To read or update, hash the key again and look in the same bucket

This gives **average-case** `O(1)` insert, lookup, and delete, assuming:
- the hash function spreads keys fairly evenly
- the table resizes before buckets get too crowded

### Collisions
Different keys can hash to the same bucket. That’s called a **collision**.

A common way to handle collisions is **separate chaining**:
- each bucket stores a small list of entries
- if multiple keys land in the same bucket, they are chained together in that list
- lookup scans only that bucket’s list

Example:
- `"cat"` → bucket 2
- `"tac"` → bucket 2
- bucket 2 stores: `[("cat", 4), ("tac", 9)]`

### Resizing
As more items are added, collisions increase. To keep performance good, hash tables usually resize when the **load factor** gets too high.

- `loadFactor = size / bucketCount`
- if it exceeds a threshold like `0.75`, create a bigger bucket array
- reinsert all existing entries using the new bucket count

### Complexity
For a good hash table:
- `get`: average `O(1)`, worst `O(n)`
- `set`: average `O(1)`, worst `O(n)`
- `delete`: average `O(1)`, worst `O(n)`

Worst case happens if many keys collide into the same bucket.

## Simple separate-chaining hash map in JavaScript
Supports:
- string keys
- integer values

```js
class HashMap {
  constructor(initialCapacity = 8) {
    this.buckets = Array.from({ length: initialCapacity }, () => []);
    this.size = 0;
    this.maxLoadFactor = 0.75;
  }

  _hash(key) {
    let hash = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < key.length; i++) {
      hash = (hash * 31 + key.charCodeAt(i)) >>> 0;
    }
    return hash;
  }

  _bucketIndex(key) {
    return this._hash(key) % this.buckets.length;
  }

  _resize() {
    const oldBuckets = this.buckets;
    this.buckets = Array.from({ length: oldBuckets.length * 2 }, () => []);
    this.size = 0;

    for (const bucket of oldBuckets) {
      for (const [key, value] of bucket) {
        this.set(key, value);
      }
    }
  }

  set(key, value) {
    if (typeof key !== 'string') {
      throw new TypeError('Key must be a string');
    }
    if (!Number.isInteger(value)) {
      throw new TypeError('Value must be an integer');
    }

    const index = this._bucketIndex(key);
    const bucket = this.buckets[index];

    for (let i = 0; i < bucket.length; i++) {
      if (bucket[i][0] === key) {
        bucket[i][1] = value;
        return;
      }
    }

    bucket.push([key, value]);
    this.size++;

    if (this.size / this.buckets.length > this.maxLoadFactor) {
      this._resize();
    }
  }

  get(key) {
    if (typeof key !== 'string') {
      throw new TypeError('Key must be a string');
    }

    const index = this._bucketIndex(key);
    const bucket = this.buckets[index];

    for (const [k, v] of bucket) {
      if (k === key) {
        return v;
      }
    }

    return undefined;
  }

  has(key) {
    return this.get(key) !== undefined;
  }

  delete(key) {
    if (typeof key !== 'string') {
      throw new TypeError('Key must be a string');
    }

    const index = this._bucketIndex(key);
    const bucket = this.buckets[index];

    for (let i = 0; i < bucket.length; i++) {
      if (bucket[i][0] === key) {
        bucket.splice(i, 1);
        this.size--;
        return true;
      }
    }

    return false;
  }
}

// Example usage
const map = new HashMap();
map.set('apple', 3);
map.set('banana', 7);
map.set('apple', 10);

console.log(map.get('apple'));  // 10
console.log(map.get('banana')); // 7
console.log(map.get('pear'));   // undefined
console.log(map.has('banana')); // true
console.log(map.delete('banana')); // true
console.log(map.has('banana')); // false
console.log(map.size); // 1
```

