A singleton ensures a class has exactly one instance and provides a global access point to it. It’s useful for shared services like logging, configuration, or caching, but should be used sparingly because global state can make testing and coupling harder.

In C#, a simple thread-safe singleton uses `Lazy<T>`, which guarantees safe, one-time initialization across threads:

```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;

public sealed class Logger
{
    private static readonly Lazy<Logger> _instance =
        new Lazy<Logger>(() => new Logger());

    private readonly object _writeLock = new object();
    private readonly string _logFilePath;

    private Logger()
    {
        _logFilePath = Path.Combine(AppDomain.CurrentDomain.BaseDirectory, "app.log");
    }

    public static Logger Instance => _instance.Value;

    public void Log(string message)
    {
        var entry = $"[{DateTime.UtcNow:O}] {message}";

        lock (_writeLock)
        {
            File.AppendAllText(_logFilePath, entry + Environment.NewLine);
        }
    }
}
```

Example usage:

```csharp
Logger.Instance.Log("Application started");
Logger.Instance.Log("Processing request");
```

Why this is thread-safe:
- `Lazy<Logger>` ensures only one `Logger` instance is created.
- `lock (_writeLock)` ensures concurrent writes don’t corrupt the log file.

If you want, I can also show a version using double-checked locking or `static readonly` initialization.

