The bottleneck is repeated DOM traversal from `querySelector` inside nested loops. Cache row/cell references once, read with indexed access (`cells[i]` / `children[i]` / a prebuilt map), and batch any DOM writes outside the loop to avoid layout/reflow churn.

```js
// Before: repeated selector lookups inside nested loops
const rows = document.querySelectorAll('table tbody tr');
const data = [];

for (const row of rows) {
  const record = {};

  for (const key of ['id', 'name', 'email', 'status']) {
    const cell = row.querySelector(`[data-col="${key}"]`);
    record[key] = cell?.textContent.trim() ?? '';
  }

  data.push(record);
}
```

```js
// After: cache structure once, then use direct access
const rows = document.querySelectorAll('table tbody tr');
const columns = ['id', 'name', 'email', 'status'];
const columnIndex = new Map(columns.map((key, i) => [key, i]));
const data = new Array(rows.length);

for (let r = 0; r < rows.length; r++) {
  const row = rows[r];
  const cells = row.cells; // live HTMLCollection, cheap indexed access
  const record = {};

  for (let c = 0; c < columns.length; c++) {
    const key = columns[c];
    record[key] = cells[columnIndex.get(key)]?.textContent.trim() ?? '';
  }

  data[r] = record;
}
```

If column order is fixed, simplify further:

```js
const rows = document.querySelectorAll('table tbody tr');
const data = new Array(rows.length);

for (let r = 0; r < rows.length; r++) {
  const cells = rows[r].cells;
  data[r] = {
    id: cells[0]?.textContent.trim() ?? '',
    name: cells[1]?.textContent.trim() ?? '',
    email: cells[2]?.textContent.trim() ?? '',
    status: cells[3]?.textContent.trim() ?? ''
  };
}
```

Big-O:

- Let `R` = rows, `C` = columns read per row, `D` = cost of selector-based DOM traversal within a row.
- Before: **O(R × C × D)** because each `querySelector` walks the row subtree again.
- After: **O(R × C)** with near-constant indexed cell access after a single row lookup.

For 5,000 rows, this removes tens of thousands of selector traversals.

Extra win if you also write to the DOM in the same loop:
- collect results first in JS
- apply DOM updates once via `DocumentFragment`, string template, or a single class/text update pass

That avoids repeated style/layout work and reduces rendering overhead.

