```java
import java.util.*;

public class OrderJoinExample {
    static class Customer {
        final long id;
        final String name;
        final String tier;

        Customer(long id, String name, String tier) {
            this.id = id;
            this.name = name;
            this.tier = tier;
        }
    }

    static class Order {
        final long id;
        final long customerId;
        String customerName;
        String customerTier;

        Order(long id, long customerId) {
            this.id = id;
            this.customerId = customerId;
        }

        void attachCustomer(Customer customer) {
            if (customer != null) {
                this.customerName = customer.name;
                this.customerTier = customer.tier;
            }
        }
    }

    // BEFORE: nested loop join
    static void attachCustomersSlow(List<Order> orders, List<Customer> customers) {
        for (Order order : orders) {
            for (Customer customer : customers) {
                if (order.customerId == customer.id) {
                    order.attachCustomer(customer);
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
    }

    // AFTER: hash join using a map
    static void attachCustomersFast(List<Order> orders, List<Customer> customers) {
        Map<Long, Customer> customersById = new HashMap<>(Math.max((int) (customers.size() / 0.75f) + 1, 16));
        for (Customer customer : customers) {
            customersById.put(customer.id, customer);
        }

        for (Order order : orders) {
            order.attachCustomer(customersById.get(order.customerId));
        }
    }
}
```

**Exact bottleneck**
- The bottleneck is the inner customer scan inside the nested loop.
- For every single order, the code linearly searches the full `customers` list until it finds a matching ID.
- With **1M orders** and **100k customers**, that means up to **100,000 comparisons per order**.

**Before optimization**
- Logic: nested loop join.
- Time complexity: **O(orders × customers)**.
- With your sizes: **O(1,000,000 × 100,000) = O(100,000,000,000)** comparisons in the worst case.
- Even average-case is still enormous: roughly half the customer list scanned per order if matches are uniformly distributed.
- Space complexity: **O(1)** extra space.

**After optimization**
- Logic: build a `HashMap<customerId, Customer>` once, then do constant-time lookups per order.
- Build map: **O(customers)**
- Join orders: **O(orders)**
- Total time complexity: **O(orders + customers)**
- With your sizes: **O(1,000,000 + 100,000) = O(1,100,000)** expected operations, plus hash overhead.
- Space complexity: **O(customers)** for the lookup map.

**Why this is the right optimization**
- The repeated ID lookup is the expensive part, so indexing customers by ID removes the repeated full scan.
- This turns the join from a quadratic-style process into a linear one for practical purposes.
- For 1M/100k-scale data, this is the standard in-memory join strategy.

**Notes**
- If `customer.id` is guaranteed unique, `HashMap` is ideal.
- If missing customer IDs are possible, `get()` returning `null` is already handled above.
- If this runs very frequently, reusing a prebuilt customer map can reduce repeated setup cost further.

