The bottleneck is the repeated linear scan of the ID vector for every query. Use a hash set (`std::unordered_set`) to preprocess the 1M IDs once, then do O(1) average-time membership checks for each of the 10M lookups.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <unordered_set>
#include <vector>

bool containsLinear(const std::vector<int>& ids, int q) {
    for (int id : ids) {
        if (id == q) return true;
    }
    return false;
}

std::vector<bool> checkQueriesFast(const std::vector<int>& ids,
                                   const std::vector<int>& queries) {
    std::unordered_set<int> idSet;
    idSet.reserve(ids.size());
    for (int id : ids) {
        idSet.insert(id);
    }

    std::vector<bool> results;
    results.reserve(queries.size());
    for (int q : queries) {
        results.push_back(idSet.find(q) != idSet.end());
    }
    return results;
}
```

### Bottleneck
The original bottleneck is this pattern:

```cpp
for (int q : queries) {
    bool found = false;
    for (int id : ids) {
        if (id == q) {
            found = true;
            break;
        }
    }
}
```

Each query scans up to all 1M IDs, so 10M queries cause an enormous number of comparisons.

### Big-O
**Before:**
- Per lookup: **O(N)**
- Total for Q lookups: **O(Q × N)**
- With N = 1,000,000 and Q = 10,000,000: about **10^13** comparisons in the worst case

**After (`std::unordered_set`):**
- Build set: **O(N)** average
- Per lookup: **O(1)** average
- Total: **O(N + Q)** average
- With N = 1,000,000 and Q = 10,000,000: roughly proportional to **11,000,000** hash operations

### Notes
- `std::unordered_set` gives the best general-purpose speedup for pure membership checks.
- If you also need sorted order, use `std::set`, but that makes lookups **O(log N)** instead of average **O(1)**.
- Calling `reserve()` helps avoid expensive rehashing during construction.

